# Midterm Proposal for MTEC-345

## What you would like to do

- My goal for this Midterm project is to generate raw audio waveforms with a GAN (probably an adapted version of WavGan from Chris Donahue), and then create a plunderphonics style composition with the generated files. There will be a few datasets, consisting of easy listening records, old dialogue and sound effects. 

- Plunderphonics relies on the cultural memory embeded in the sampled audio, however by being dependent on the model "hallucinating", I am putting it in a liminal space between something human and something machine. 

- Generating WAV files will be crucial, as I am capturing the degradation of the sound itself, and targeting the GANS inability to understand context. Easy listening and vintage dialogue often carry heavy and comforting nostalgia. By having a neural network attempt to reconstruct these sounds. which I will then piece myself together, I am creating something reminiscent of a deteriorating memory.

## How you will do it

- Chris Donahue's WavGan uses 1D convolutions to generate raw audio samples directly. The grittiness of it as demonstrated with Aiphex Twin's "Noise to Water" shows that it is aesthetically coherent. When it fails, it will fail with tape-like digital artifacts rather than something blurry which is often the result of using an AI model that generates spectrograms. 

- I will need to source and format hours of easy listening and specific audio. This is trickier than it sounds because if the dataset varies too much it will simply output white noise. I will need to be particular with my samples, for example only using easy listening that contains orchestral arrangement, spoken word only by women, etc. 

- Once I collect these samples, I will need to write a batch script to chop, downsample and format my datasets into uniform 1-4 second clips. This is because WaveGan prefers being fed audio samples at 16kHz. The neural network
Questions, concerns, and stretch goals

- GAN consists of two neural networks locked in a feedback loop. One generates fake audio, and the other listens to my curated datasets and what the generator has faked, trying to guess which is which. When it has gone one full pass through my dataset, this is known as an epoch. 

- Unfortunately, this takes an immense amount of GPU power, and each dataset would take at minimum 10 days of continuous training, and since I only have a single machine this would take a month of continuous computing time.  This would also make it impossible for me to do any other work other this time.

- The workaround for this is to move the computing to a cloud, allowing me to keep using my laptop in the meantime. There are services such as Google Colab Pro, which would allow me to rent a data center GPU. The only drawback would be that I would have to "babysit" the training proccess, keeping the laptop open. If colab disconnects a second time it will wipe the hard drive completely. To avoid losing progress, I will need to create a python script that mounts it to my google drive and the command-line flags required to make WaveGan resume from the saved checkpoint.

- Since I am looking for artifacts and glitches, I will need to configure my training script to save snapshots of the model's brain every few hundred epochs, which will capture the neural network at various stages of confusion. The goal will be towards the middle/end, where early checkpoints will sound harsh. The middle and end will sound closest to the original samples. Once I find the checkpoint I will instruct the generator to export hundreds of unique wav files.

- From there I will put these files in my DAW, and Frankenstein everything together.


## Questions, concerns and stretch goals

- Questions I have for myself are how I would set up the Python environment required to get the WavGAN repository running on my machine.
- How large should my dataset be?
- Not a question but I am curious as to how the cloud GPU instance will handle this. Overall very curious about this trial and error proccess.

- My concerns revolve around the uncertainties of the things I previously stated. It is a very high resource-intensive and time-consuming task. There is also the daunting task of having to mix the files. AI audio tends to have chaotic sub-frequencies, DC offsets and piercing resonances which will need to be removed to prevent the mix from hurting the listener.